{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620656"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:45:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:45:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16641"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16641"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.18,0.09,0.18,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9332"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76688"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9332"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16641"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62180"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"},{"type":"tags","id":"5061"},{"type":"tags","id":"5190"},{"type":"tags","id":"5192"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22638"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76688"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAtomoxetine is a medication approved for the treatment of attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) as an alternative to stimulant medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of atomoxetine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stimulates release of serotonin in the frontal cortex","Blocks dopamine reuptake in the nucleus accumbens","Inhibits monoamine oxidase enzyme","Acts as a direct dopamine receptor agonist in the frontal cortex","Inhibits noradrenaline reuptake in the prefrontal cortex"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAtomoxetine works by \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting noradrenaline reuptake in the prefrontal cortex\u003C/strong\u003E. This increases noradrenergic neurotransmission, which helps improve attention and executive function in ADHD patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates release of serotonin in the frontal cortex \u003C/strong\u003E: atomoxetine does not significantly affect serotonergic neurotransmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks dopamine reuptake in the nucleus accumbens\u003C/strong\u003E: this mechanism is characteristic of stimulant medications such as methylphenidate, whereas atomoxetine has minimal effect on dopamine signalling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits monoamine oxidase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes the mechanism of monoamine oxidase inhibitors, which affect multiple neurotransmitter systems rather than being selective for noradrenaline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActs as a direct dopamine receptor agonist in the frontal cortex \u003C/strong\u003E: atomoxetine does not interact with dopamine receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnlike stimulant medications, atomoxetine has minimal effect on dopamine in the nucleus accumbens, which explains its lower potential for abuse. Its selective action on noradrenaline in the prefrontal cortex makes it an effective alternative for ADHD treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atomoxetine is a selective noradrenaline reuptake inhibitor that increases noradrenergic neurotransmission in the prefrontal cortex","Non-stimulant medications for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder work through different mechanisms than stimulants.","Atomoxetine does not affect dopamine levels in the nucleus accumbens, reducing its potential for abuse."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62180"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16641"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62180"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T09:52:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T09:52:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9332"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76688"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":